<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the synthetic demo user
    `x_[scope]_demo_viewer`. This is the third of the three demo personas
    created by the case-management POC scoped application; companions are
    `x_[scope]_demo_manager` and `x_[scope]_demo_agent`.

    Persona role (per AAP Section 0.5.6 ACL Matrix):
      This user is the READ-ONLY operational demo persona. After the
      companion role-assignment row at
      ../role_assignments/sys_user_has_role_x_[scope]_demo_viewer.xml
      grants this user the scoped role `x_[scope]_case_viewer`, this user
      gets:
        - x_[scope]_case        Read All; NO Create / NO Write / NO Delete
        - x_[scope]_case_task   Read All; NO Create / NO Write / NO Delete
        - x_[scope]_case_party  Read All; NO Create / NO Write / NO Delete
      Unlike the case_agent persona, the viewer's read scope is NOT
      restricted to "Assigned only" — the viewer can read every record in
      the three custom tables regardless of `assigned_agent`/
      `assigned_group`.

    Validation Gate 3 dependency (AAP Section 0.7.3):
      The operator impersonates this user to verify the gate's pass row
      "case_viewer cannot write." If this user is able to save any case
      form change, write a new task, or delete any record, Gate 3 fails.
      The absence of write privileges is enforced at the ACL layer
      (../../acl/x_[scope]_case_*_viewer*.xml — only READ ACLs exist for
      this role); no client-side or business-rule guard is required.

    Why this user record lives in the SCOPED Update Set even though
    `sys_user` is a global OOB table (per the agent prompt and AAP
    Section 0.7.2 scope-namespace exclusivity):
      The scoped Update Set's deliverable is fully self-contained: the
      reviewer must be able to install the Update Set on a fresh PDI and
      immediately exercise all seven validation gates. The three demo
      personas (manager, agent, viewer) are required by Gate 3 (ACL role-
      based access) and Gate 4 (portal submission as an unauthenticated
      requester routed to a queue visible to the demo agent). Tracking
      the demo personas inside the scoped Update Set ensures they import
      together with the rest of the application; the scope binding via
      <sys_scope> and <sys_package> source attribute groups them with the
      scoped app even though their parent table (sys_user) is global. No
      global-scope WRITES are performed: only INSERTS into sys_user (a
      data table) — the OOB sys_user dictionary, ACLs, and form layouts
      are never modified.

    Why this user is NOT a member of the demo group `x_[scope]_demo_team`
    (per the agent prompt key insight #6):
      Only the demo AGENT is added to the demo group, because the agent's
      read/write privileges are gated by "Assigned only" — i.e., agent
      can only see cases where `assigned_agent = current user OR
      assigned_group contains current user`. The viewer's role grants
      Read-All across the three tables (no group-membership condition),
      so demo-team membership is irrelevant for the viewer's privileges.
      Adding the viewer to the demo group would be harmless but
      misleading.

    Why this user does NOT get used as `assigned_agent` on any case (per
    the agent prompt and round_trip_verify.md acceptance test):
      The case_viewer role explicitly forbids write access. If the viewer
      were the assigned_agent on a case, the field-level ACL on
      x_[scope]_case.assigned_agent (write restricted to case_manager and
      assigned case_agent) would block normal case operations. Only the
      demo AGENT is used as `assigned_agent` and `assigned_to` in the
      seed data.

    Authoring rules honored (per AAP Sections 0.7.1 / 0.7.2 and the
    agent prompt's eight authoring rules):

      Rule 1 — No PII:
        first_name = "Demo" (literal, not a real first name)
        last_name  = "Viewer" (the role title as a synthetic surname —
                     unmistakably non-real; no real person's last name
                     would be "Viewer")
        email      = "demo-viewer@example.invalid" (the .invalid TLD is
                     reserved by RFC 2606 / BCP 32; never resolves to a
                     real domain — guarantees no accidental email leak)
        NO phone, NO mobile_phone, NO home_phone, NO business_phone,
        NO address fields, NO birthdate, NO SSN, NO photo,
        NO realistic full names, NO realistic email addresses.

      Rule 2 — No hardcoded cross-reference sys_ids:
        The user's OWN <sys_id> below is the record's primary key, which
        is acceptable per AAP rule (it is NOT a reference to any other
        record). It is a deterministic 32-character lowercase hex value
        (MD5 of the canonical user_name "x_[scope]_demo_viewer") so the
        Update Set engine resolves the same sys_id on every PDI import,
        making the role-assignment and party `person` cross-references
        idempotent.
        The <sys_scope> and <sys_package> reference fields resolve by
        display_value/source attributes against the scoped application's
        sys_scope record — NOT by hardcoded sys_id literals.
        NO <manager>, <department>, <location>, <company> reference
        fields are populated, so no other reference-resolution concerns
        arise.

      Rule 3 — No password:
        The <user_password/> element is empty (self-closing). A populated
        password (even hashed) in an Update Set XML would be an obvious
        credential leak risk. Demo users are signed in via the OOB
        `admin` impersonation feature in the PDI UI; they do NOT need a
        set password.

      Rule 4 — Scope binding:
        <sys_scope> binds this user record to the scoped application
        whose sys_scope.source is `x_[scope]` (defined in
        ../../app/sys_scope/x_[scope].xml). The display_value attribute
        is "Case Management". The <sys_package> follows the same pattern
        with the source attribute pointing at the scope source name.
        This matches the convention used by every other scoped artifact
        in the Update Set (roles, ACLs, dictionary entries, choices,
        etc.).

      Rule 5 — Idempotency anchor:
        The user's idempotent key is <user_name> = "x_[scope]_demo_viewer".
        The companion seed script ../../scripts/seed_demo_data.js
        ensureUser() helper queries sys_user by user_name BEFORE
        inserting; the action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE" attribute on the inner
        <sys_user> element ensures the same behavior at Update Set
        import time. This <user_name> value MUST EXACTLY match every
        downstream reference: the role assignment row at
        ../role_assignments/sys_user_has_role_x_[scope]_demo_viewer.xml,
        the seed script's DEMO.USERS.VIEWER constant, and any party
        `person` field on case 05's Requester party row.

      Rule 6 — No production data:
        No real first names, last names, email addresses, phone numbers,
        addresses, or any other personally identifiable information. The
        synthetic placeholder values (Demo, Viewer, demo-viewer@example
        .invalid) are unmistakably non-real.

      Rule 7 — Minimum field set:
        ONLY the minimum content fields required by the AAP template are
        populated: active, email, first_name, last_name, user_name,
        user_password (empty). All additional sys_user columns (manager,
        department, phone, mobile_phone, home_phone, business_phone,
        title, location, company, photo, time_zone, date_format,
        introduction, source, u_*) are auto-defaulted by the platform on
        first import. This keeps the file small, avoids dependencies on
        other global tables (cmn_department, cmn_location, core_company),
        and makes the record resilient to ServiceNow release-version
        drift.

      Rule 8 — Scoped Update Set XML conventions:
        Root element: <record_update table="sys_user">
        Inner element: <sys_user action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE"> for
        idempotent re-import per AAP Section 0.7.1 round-trip-
        verification.
        UTF-8 encoding declared in XML prolog.
        Boolean values lowercase: <active>true</active>.
        Element ordering: alphabetical (matching the role records and
        every other XML in the scoped Update Set).

    Cross-dependencies (per AAP Section 0.5.2):

      This user IS REFERENCED BY (these files resolve THIS user by
      <user_name> = "x_[scope]_demo_viewer", NOT by sys_id literal):
        - ../role_assignments/sys_user_has_role_x_[scope]_demo_viewer.xml
            grants this user the x_[scope]_case_viewer role
        - any Person-type demo party that uses this user as the `person`
          reference (per the seed-script's party table — case 05
          Requester party in the canonical seed list)
        - ../../scripts/seed_demo_data.js  (the DEMO.USERS.VIEWER
          constant equals this user_name)

      This user IS NOT referenced by:
        - any case's `assigned_agent` field (only x_[scope]_demo_agent
          is assigned)
        - any task's `assigned_to` field (only x_[scope]_demo_agent
          is assigned)
        - the demo group's sys_user_grmember membership row (the viewer
          is intentionally NOT a member of x_[scope]_demo_team)

      Update Set ordering (per AAP Section 0.5.2):
        - This record MUST be loaded AFTER the scope/app records under
          ../../app/ (since <sys_scope>/<sys_package> reference the
          scope's source).
        - This record MUST be loaded BEFORE:
            * the role assignment at ../role_assignments/
              sys_user_has_role_x_[scope]_demo_viewer.xml (resolves
              <user> by user_name lookup — needs this user to exist)
            * any Person-type demo party that references this user as
              `person` by user_name lookup

    Source-side semantic reference (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported)
    per AAP Section 0.8.1:
      - acm-services/acm-service-users/src/main/java/com/armedia/acm/
        services/users/model/ApplicationRolesConfig.java
        Holds `application.roles` as a List<String> bound from external
        configuration via @ListValue("application.roles"). Semantic
        anchor only: ArkCase's role-name list pattern (which would have
        included a viewer/observer-tier role) is replaced in the target
        by named scoped roles. This demo user is the principal that gets
        granted the x_[scope]_case_viewer role via the separate role-
        assignment record.
      - ArkCase's underlying `acm_user` table (defined by AcmUser.java,
        LDAP/AD-backed in production) is NOT replicated; the ServiceNow
        target uses fully synthetic in-platform users on the OOB
        sys_user table.

    Validation hooks (per the agent prompt):
      - The XML well-formedness check (xmllint with no-output flag)
        returns zero errors.
      - No-PII grep returns zero matches against (john|jane|smith|doe|
        mary|maria|@gmail|@yahoo|@outlook|@hotmail|\.com|\.org|\.net).
      - No-extra-fields grep returns zero matches against (manager|
        department|phone|mobile_phone|home_phone|business_phone|title|
        location|company|photo|introduction|date_format|time_zone|
        source).
      - Empty-password grep returns zero matches against a populated
        user_password element of the form open-tag CHARS close-tag.
      - The user_name value matches downstream references exactly.
-->
<record_update table="sys_user">
    <sys_user action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <active>true</active>
        <email>demo-viewer@example.invalid</email>
        <first_name>Demo</first_name>
        <last_name>Viewer</last_name>
        <sys_class_name>sys_user</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_id>912ca3946a0f74c22d5b7c2e7e143771</sys_id>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_[scope]">x_[scope]</sys_package>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_[scope]</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>sys_user_x_[scope]_demo_viewer</sys_update_name>
        <user_name>x_[scope]_demo_viewer</user_name>
        <user_password/>
    </sys_user>
</record_update>
